    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-05-20T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-05-20T03:00:00-05:00" n="815"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d815">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">867N.01/1557: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Fish</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-05-20T10:00:00+02:00"
                            >May 20, 1939—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 20—7:33 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>58. The British White Paper on Palestine is strongly criticized in the Arabic
                    press and has aroused considerable disappointment. On May 18th the Prime
                    Minister made a declaration to the press substantially as follows: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Seeing that the British Government have not accepted the demands made by
                            the Governments of the Arab countries…<note n="71" xml:id="d815fn71"
                                >Omission indicated in the original telegram.</note> these
                            Governments are unable to recommend to the people of Palestine to
                            collaborate with the British authorities on the basis of the British
                            Government’s plan. We are continuing to collaborate as between the
                            Governments of the Arab powers but as the British have now defined their
                            policy we consider that the negotiations are ended”.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Wafdist circles seize upon the White Paper to attack both the British and the
                    Egyptian Governments, derogate last month’s Arab <pb facs="0766" n="760"
                        xml:id="pg_760"/> conversations in Cairo and charge that England has placed
                    hands on Palestine forever. Deputy Abdul Hamid Said, President of the Young
                    Men’s Moslem Association, cabled a protest on May 18th to Chamberlain to the
                    effect that British policy as now stated is designed to Judaize Palestine.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Fish</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
